As noted in section \ref{sec:econ_metab},
the economy is society's metabolism.\index{economic metabolism}
As such, the economy exhibits characteristics of a metabolism\index{economic metabolism}:
it ingests materials and emits wastes\index{waste}.
These characteristics of the economic metabolism\index{economic metabolism} are captured by the
final term in Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX} (repeated below for convenience),
the environmental impacts of resource extraction\index{resource extraction} and consumption~\Xparen{}, 
the topic of this chapter.

\begin{equation} 
  \iparx            \tag{\ref{eq:IPARX}}
\end{equation}

The impact of resources~\Xparen{}
is related to
the types and quantities of resources consumed and the 
ways of processing those resources. 
%Environmental impact intensity is discussed in this chapter.
Resources are the inputs to the economy 
(``food'' in the metabolic analogy), and 
environmental impacts come from the economy's excreted wastes\index{waste}.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Impacts of resources}
\label{sec:impact_intensity}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

The impacts of resources~\Xparen{}
is defined as
%
\begin{equation}\label{eq:X}
  \mft{X} \equiv \frac{\textrm{total environmental impacts produced}}{\textrm{total resources extracted}} \; .
\end{equation}
%
Note that ``impacts'' are plural.
Extracting and consuming all the resources necessary to make the economy run 
will have effects on air, water, species diversity, land, and human communities.%
\footnote{
  If you are comfortable with matrix notation, 
  \mft{X} can be thought of as a matrix with
  resources in rows and impacts in columns.  
}
%
Examples of environmental impacts include
water eutrophication\index{eutrophication} (from fertilizer runoff),
SO$_2$\index{sulfur dioxide (SO$_2$)!emissions of} emissions (from burning sulfurous coal\index{coal}),
CO$_2$ emissions (from burning fossil fuels),
desertification\index{desertification}
(due to overcultivation of crops, overgrazing of livestock, and alien species invasion), and
species loss\index{species loss} (due to habitat loss\index{habitat loss},
environmental toxins, and over-exploitation).
With reference to a few of the critical materials in Table~\ref{tab:CRMs},
other examples of environmental impacts caused by resource extraction\index{resource extraction} and consumption include:
%
\begin{itemize}

  \item air, water, and soil pollution\index{pollution!air}\index{pollution!water}\index{pollution!soil}~\cite{Lee:2017ui} 
        in the form of
        bauxite dust,\index{bauxite!dust}
        sulfur dioxide (SO$_2$), and
        nitrous oxides (NO$_\mathrm{x}$) emissions\index{nitrous oxides (NO$_\mathrm{x}$)!emissions of}
        from bauxite mining in Australia;

  \item toxic tailings
        from tungsten\index{tungsten (W)}
        mining operations in Korea~\cite{Lee:2021tz}; and

  \item deforestation\index{deforestation} and
        reduced forest quality~\cite{Kissinger:2020ut}
        to make way for rubber plantations\index{rubber plantations}
        in southeast Asia.

\end{itemize}


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Example: carbon intensity of energy}\index{carbon intensity of primary energy}
\label{sec:carbon_intensity_of_energy}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

As discussed in Chapter~\ref{chap:resource_intensity},
our prime example for resource extraction\index{resource extraction} and consumption is energy.
Because CO$_2$ emissions
are a significant source of environmental impact
from energy consumption,
it follows that the prime example of 
environmental impact of resources 
(\;\!\mft{X} in Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}) is CO$_2$ emissions
in tonnes per MJ of energy provided.
Specifically, the prime example for impact of resources~\Xparen{}
is the CO$_2$ intensity of energy~(\;\!$\mft{X}_{\text{CO}_2}$).
$\mft{X}_{\text{CO}_2}$ is an intensity, because
carbon (numerator) can be considered an input 
to energy derived from fossil fuels (denominator).

Figure~\ref{fig:LLNL_CO2_sankey} is a Sankey diagram
of sources of CO$_2$ emissions from the U.S.\ economy in 2018.
