The biofuel\index{traditional biofuel}-to-fossil-fuel transition has
significant sustainability implications.
Traditional biofuels\index{traditional biofuel} are carbon neutral\index{carbon neutral},
because any CO$_2$ released by combustion was
already sequestered into the biomass as the plants grew.
Fossil fuels are not carbon neutral\index{carbon neutral};
their combustion releases CO$_2$ that was sequestered millions of years ago.
As the world transitioned away from traditional biofuels\index{traditional biofuel} toward fossil fuels,
the carbon intensity of primary energy\index{carbon intensity of primary energy} rose.

On the other hand, use of traditional biofuels\index{traditional biofuel} results in deforestation\index{deforestation}, erosion,
and other negative environmental effects (as well as being inefficient from an
EROI\index{energy return on investment (EROI)}
perspective, as shown in Table~\ref{tab:eroi}).
The transition away from biofuel\index{biofuel} consumption results in cleaner urban air (especially after 
the transition from coal\index{coal} to natural gas\index{natural gas} for residential heating)~\cite{Gordon2016}.
Because having a healthy environment is what economists call a ``normal'' good,
\mft{I} should fall as \mft{A} rises, in general.
In some ways (but not in terms of CO$_2$ emissions and climate change\index{climate change}),
the transition away from traditional biofuels\index{traditional biofuel} did result
in reduced environmental impact.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Reducing the carbon intensity of energy}\index{carbon intensity of primary energy}
\label{sec:reducing_c}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX} shows that reducing any of the right-hand side terms to 0
will eliminate CO$_2$ emissions.
That is, if any of 
population~\Pparen{}, 
affluence~\Aparen{},
energy intensity of economic activity (\REp{}, the prime example for \mft{R}),
or
carbon intensity of primary energy\index{carbon intensity of primary energy}
(\;\!\XCOtwo{}, the prime example for \mft{X}\:)
goes to zero,
CO$_2$ emissions will be eliminated.
Few people want to reduce population~\Pparen{} or affluence~\Aparen{}.
The primary energy intensity\index{primary energy intensity}
of the economy~\REpparen{} is declining
(Figure~\ref{fig:EnergyIntensityGraph-Nordhaus}),
but not as fast as population (\mft{P}, Figure~\ref{fig:PopulationGraph}) and
affluence (\mft{A}, Figure~\ref{fig:AffluenceGraph-Nordhaus})
are growing. 
By the process of elimination, 
reducing the carbon intensity of primary energy\index{carbon intensity of primary energy}~\XCOtwoparen{} 
is often considered to be the 
only politically and socially viable way to move in a sustainable direction
with respect to the prime example of energy and CO$_2$ emissions.

Figure~\ref{fig:ImpactIntensityGraph} shows that 
the carbon intensity of primary energy\index{carbon intensity of primary energy}~\XCOtwoparen{}
rose dramatically from 1800--1960, 
as use of fossil fuels came to dominate the world energy story;
see Figure~\ref{fig:PrimaryEnergyGraph}.
Since 1960, the carbon intensity of primary energy\index{carbon intensity of primary energy}
has hovered around 63~MtCO$_2$/EJ.
Thus, for the last 60~years, \XCOtwo{} has been stubbornly constant
and far too high for environmental sustainability\index{environmental sustainability}
(both weak\index{weak sustainability} and strong\index{strong sustainability}).
It appears that eliminating CO$_2$ emissions by significantly reducing
\XCOtwo{} will require unprecedented changes
to the world's primary energy\index{primary energy} supply.
But how?


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Transition to a low-carbon energy regime}
\label{sec:low_carbon_transition}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

There are at least seven often-discussed options for
transitioning to a low carbon energy supply:
(a) carbon capture and storage,
(b) carbon sequestration\index{carbon sequestration},
(c) carbon takeback obligation,
(d) carbon tax,
(e) nuclear electricity,
(e) biomass, and
(f) wind, water, and solar (WWS).
Each option has its own challenges and 
none has yet been implemented on a large enough scale to reduce CO$_2$ emissions;
see Figure~\ref{fig:CarbonEmissionsGraph}.
The subsections below discuss these options and their implementation challenges.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Carbon capture and storage}
\label{sec:ccs}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Carbon capture and storage (CCS)\index{carbon capture and storage (CCS)}
is a way to continue using fossil fuels
during a transition to a low-carbon energy regime. 
In a CCS electricity plant, 
CO$_2$ emissions are captured at the smokestack
and routed underground.
The CO$_2$ is stored, presumably in perpetuity, in caverns or other underground formations.
CCS is not a low-carbon form of energy.
Rather, CCS is a way to avoid carbon emissions from carbon-based energy production.

There are several challenges associated with CCS.
First, it has not been cost-effective.  
Petra Nova\index{Petra Nova}, the only CCS plant in the U.S., disposed of the CO$_2$ it captured
by injecting it into oil fields for enhanced oil recovery.
In 2020, low oil prices made this disposal infeasible, forcing Petra Nova to shut down.
This story illustrates the economic interrelation(s) among primary energy\index{primary energy} sources.
Second, a fossil-fuel power plant fitted with CCS technology 
must ensure that CO$_2$ emissions remain buried. 
If the CO$_2$ escapes to the atmosphere, the effort is ineffective.
Third, there are limited locations with the required underground geological formations 
for CCS.
Finally, CCS is not applicable to CO$_2$ emissions from transportation,
which is the plurality of CO$_2$ emissions; 
see Table~\ref{tab:corrected_co2_emissions}.
It would be impractical to fit every car with a ``CO$_2$ diaper''
to collect CO$_2$ emissions for later injection underground.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Carbon sequestration}\index{carbon sequestration}
\label{sec:carbon_sequestration}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Carbon sequestration\index{carbon sequestration} seeks to extract CO$_2$ from the atmosphere,
storing it in inert form.
One form of carbon sequestration\index{carbon sequestration} is simply planting billions of trees.
A massive, worldwide afforestation effort would be required to extract
the additional carbon that has been added to the atmosphere since the industrial revolution.
In such a scheme, trees consume CO$_2$ and store it in their biomass.
Unfortunately, if the trees are burned or die and decompose, 
the CO$_2$ is returned to the atmosphere.

Alternatively, direct air capture extracts CO$_2$ from the atmosphere,
typically using huge banks of fans and an adsorbent.
Direct air capture is extremely energy intensive because of the heat needed
to regenerate the adsorbents. 
Additional energy consumption for sequestration
lowers the net EROI\index{energy return on investment (EROI)}
of fossil energy production; see Section~\ref{sec:masterE}.
Additionally, because atmospheric CO$_2$ concentrations\index{atmospheric CO$_2$ concentration} are low, massive amounts
of air need to be moved, which makes operating the fans 
both 
monetarily expensive 
and
energy intensive.
Some carbon sequestration\index{carbon sequestration} technologies require expensive and/or rare
materials.
Various schemes have been proposed for how to alleviate some or all of these problems,
but none have been proven to work at scale.

One additional problem with carbon sequestration is selecting the form for 
ultimate storage. 
Geologic storage converts CO$_2$ to liquid form at high pressure and pumps it underground.
Biologic storage is when carbon is trapped in plant matter, soil, or aquatic
environments.
Some have suggested storing CO$_2$ in a stable chemical structure such as graphene.
No consensus has emerged to date.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Carbon takeback obligation}
\label{sec:ctbo}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Another way to reduce CO$_2$ emissions over time is the 
carbon takeback obligation (CTBO)~\cite{Jenkins:2021tg}.\index{carbon takeback obligation (CTBO)}
The CTBO is similar to product takeback policies
which require manufacturers to accept end-of-life product returns from consumers,
thereby keeping wastes\index{waste} (refrigerators, washers, dryers, computers, electronics, and other products)
out of landfills and 
contaminants out of the environment.

The climate change\index{climate change} equivalent of a product takeback is the carbon takeback. 
Under a CTBO, fossil fuel producers and importers would be required 
to permanently sequester the CO$_2$ emitted from the fossil fuels they sell or import.
Industries that emit greenhouse gases (cement making, for example)
would also be required to sequester their emissions.
A CTBO does not specify how the sequestration must occur,
but it specifies who is obliged to perform the sequestration. 
Under a CTBO, fossil fuel producers and other emitting industries
would be free to pass the cost of carbon sequestration\index{carbon sequestration}
to fossil fuel users and other product purchasers (cement buyers, for example),
thereby internalizing the cost of CO$_2$ emissions in the economy.
Consumers would still be free to purchase and use fossil fuels, 
but under a CTBO, the cost of externalities would be evident
in the price. 

A progressive CTBO could be phased over several years.
In the first years, only, say, 10\% of emitted CO$_2$ would need to be sequestered.
A few years later, 20\%.
Then 30\%.
Eventually, fossil fuel producers and other emitting industries
would need to be sequester 100\% of the
greenhouse gases emitted from the use of their product.

There are several implementation challenges for CTBOs.
First, we will need to develop the expertise to 
sequester carbon on a scale never seen before.
(At present, only 0.1\% of emitted carbon in sequestered~\cite[p.~2777]{Jenkins:2021tg}.)
Second, policymakers will need to develop rules and laws for CTBOs, 
and enforcement mechanisms will need to be implemented.
Finally, lower-carbon alternatives will need to be developed for many 
commonplace technologies, including
transport (ground and air), 
building materials (especially cement), and 
building heating and cooling.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Carbon taxes and offsets}
\label{sec:carbon_tax_offsets}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Carbon taxes\index{carbon tax} impose financial penalties on emitters of greenhouse gases.
Emitters pass costs to consumers who face higher prices for goods and services
created with carbon-intensive energy.
Consumers will, over time, prefer lower-cost goods, 
thereby incentivizing manufacturers and service providers
to use low-carbon energy.

Carbon offsets\index{carbon offset} enable carbon emitters to
pay someone else to sequester or reduce carbon emissions.
Carbon emissions are traded as a financial instrument.
A market develops in which emissions and reductions are traded, 
with competition leading to low prices for net emission reductions.
As such, carbon offsets 
enable carbon emitters to shift the responsibility for implementing
emissions reductions.

Both carbon taxes and carbon offsets are 
financial approaches that encourage transitions to a low-carbon energy supply.
Both taxes and offsets nudge consumer and producer behaviors
in the direction of low-carbon energy supply.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Nuclear electricity}
\label{sec:nuclear_electricity}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Nuclear power\index{nuclear energy} (an electricity source only)
may provide a bridge to a sustainable future.
Nuclear power emits little CO$_2$ during plant operation
and has high EROI; see Table~\ref{tab:eroi}. 
However, the energy cost to construct a nuclear power plant 
is higher than other types of
electricity production plants.
In addition, 
it is energy-intensive to mine and refine uranium prior to its use
in a nuclear power plant. 
If the energy required to construct nuclear energy plants
and refine uranium comes from fossil fuels, 
significant CO$_2$ emissions will result from the transition to nuclear electricity.
An additional consideration is the availability of uranium resources,
the topic of \ref{project:nuclear_resources}.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Biomass}
\label{sec:biomass}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

In lieu of extracting CO$_2$ from the atmosphere,
we could stop emitting CO$_2$ from fossil fuel combustion in the first place!
One way is to transition away from fossil fuels 
to the energy mix used in the first half of the 19$^{\text{th}}$ century,
namely exclusive use of traditional biofuels\index{traditional biofuel} (wood and wood products)
for heating and electricity;
see Figure~\ref{fig:PrimaryEnergyGraph}.
However, supplying the energy needs of today's economy would be impossible:
we don't have enough available arable land
to grow the required amount of biomass.
(Proof of this statement is left for \ref{project:biofuel_proof}.)
Even if there were enough land, today's methods of growing crops requires
unsustainable energy, water, and chemical inputs;
see Chapter \ref{chap:agriculture}.

Biomass (unmodified wood or wood pellets) 
works well for home heating and cooking
via wood stoves, 
provided that particulate matter\index{particulate matter (PM)} emissions are mitigated appropriately.
However, biomass by itself is not electricity or liquid fuel.
A conversion to biomass for the world's primary energy\index{primary energy} supply would also require 
worldwide replacement of today's fossil fuel electricity generation infrastructure
with a fleet of biomass power plants.
And conversion to biomass would require build-out 
of a biomass-to-liquid-fuels conversion 
infrastructure that does not yet exist.
Finally, conversion to biomass will be accompanied by a reduction 
in EROI\index{energy return on investment (EROI)}; 
see Section~\ref{sec:masterE}.
The EROI\index{energy return on investment (EROI)} for fossil fuels is mostly greater than 20, while
the EROI\index{energy return on investment (EROI)} for corn ethanol\index{corn ethanol}
is typically less than 2~\cite{Hammerschlag:2006uf};
see Table \ref{tab:eroi}.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Wind, water, and solar electricity}
\label{sec:wws}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

We could transition the world's energy system
to water (hydro), wind, and solar 
energy sources (WWS)~\cite{Jacobson:2011gc,Delucchi:2011gb}.\index{wind, water, and solar (WWS)}
A transition to WWS would also require 
significant changes to the world's energy infrastructure, 
with at least four large challenges.

First, WWS energy resources produce electricity, not liquid fuels, and 
large changes will be needed.
For example, today's transport sector is almost exclusively powered 
by liquid fossil fuels (gasoline\index{gasoline} and diesel) and illustrates two options for 
transitioning from today's energy system to a WWS energy system.
The first option is to replace
all fossil-fuel vehicles with \textbf{electric vehicles}\index{electric vehicle (EV)},
as is slowly occurring today. 
Electrification of personal vehicles is happening from the top end of the market, 
with expensive offerings from companies such as Tesla\index{Tesla}.
(Electrification has not yet penetrated meaningfully into the freight system,
including trucks, ships, and planes.)
The second option is to use WWS electricity 
in plants that convert biomass feedstocks\index{feedstock} to biofuels\index{biofuel}.

Deployment of a WWS energy system provides a second challenge:
wind and solar are intermittent sources of electricity,
while today's electricity sources 
(coal\index{coal}, natural gas\index{natural gas}, nuclear, and hydro)
are constant.
At present, electric grids accommodate only a fraction 
of intermittent electricity, much less than 100\%.
So a transition to wind and solar primary energy\index{primary energy} sources will require
redesign and reimplementation of electricity grids worldwide
to include electricity storage.

There are several options for grid-scale electricity storage, including
batteries and potential energy storage.
Battery storage will require great quantities of rare earth metals 
and other exotic materials, 
already included on lists of critical raw materials\index{critical raw materials (CRMs)};
see Section~\ref{sec:resources_strong_sustainability}. 
Gravitational potential energy could supply energy storage with nearly 100\% 
round-trip efficiency.
Options for potential energy storage materials include 
water (with a pumped hydro plant)\index{pumped hydro}
or concrete with a system such as Energy Vault~\cite{Energy-Vault:uz}.

A third challenge comes from the water portion of WWS. 
In most areas of the world, 
the potential for expanding the production of hydro electricity is limited.
Most of the Americas, Europe, and Asia are already ``tapped out'' regarding hydropower.
Today, the potential for hydro is greatest in central Africa.
The proposed Grand Inga Dam in the Democratic Republic of the Congo
would be the largest dam in the world and could house a 40--70 GW hydro power station.
Moreover, there are considerable negative environmental and social impacts from 
hydro projects, such as changes to soil salinity, silting, and the destruction
of communities located in the proposed reservoir.

Finally, WWS systems are energy intensive to manufacture.
So the transition to a WWS future will require significant energy investment
in addition to significant financial investment.
If the energy investment to make WWS systems comes from fossil fuels,
significant CO$_2$ will be emitted during the transition
from today's energy regime to a WWS regime.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Speed of energy transitions}\index{energy transitions}
\label{sec:Etransitions}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Figure \ref{fig:ImpactIntensityGraph} shows that a transition to a new form(s)
of energy takes quite a long time to complete. It is costly both in terms of
money and resources, in particular, in terms of energy itself.
It takes energy to make energy-making machines!

Energy historians find that energy transitions often take decades to complete.
Roger Fouquet\index{Fouquet, Roger} has studied energy transitions of the UK in many economic sectors and 
across many energy technologies.
He found that
``since the Industrial Revolution, it took, on average, 
nearly 50 years for energy transitions 
(i.e., the diffusion of energy sources and technologies) 
to unfold''~\cite[p.~6595]{Fouquet:2010tq}.
Given that we have only about a decade before we are committed to 1.5~\degC{} warming
(Section~\ref{sec:GHGCC}), 
50~years is too long.
Large-scale investment to support 
a full-scale transition to a carbon-free energy system 
needs to start yesterday!


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Revisiting the IPARX identity}\index{IPARX identity}
\label{sec:revisit_IPARX}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Chapters~\ref{chap:planetary_boundaries}--\ref{chap:impact_intensity}
show the evolution of all terms in the IPARX identity\index{IPARX identity} (Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX})
over the period 1800--2019
for the prime example of energy consumption and CO$_2$ emissions.
It is instructive to quantify the magnitude and direction of changes 
in the right-side terms for the prime example of energy and CO$_2$ emissions
(\:\!\mft{P}, \mft{A}, \REp{}, and \XCOtwo). 
To do so, we introduce a rate version of the IPARX identity\index{IPARX identity}.

In the rate version of the IPARX identity\index{IPARX identity}, each term is represented 
by an exponential rate of change (\mft{r}\:\!), measured in \%/year.
The rate version of the IPARX identity\index{IPARX identity} indicates 
which terms are moving in a sustainable direction (\mft{r} < 0) and
which terms are moving in an unsustainable direction (\mft{r} > 0).

\begin{equation} \label{eq:IPARX_rate}
  \mft{r}_\mft{I} \approx \mft{r}_\mft{P} + \mft{r}_\mft{A} + \mft{r}_\mft{R} + \mft{r}_\mft{X}
\end{equation}
%
Each rate (\mft{r}\:\!) is calculated by

\begin{equation} \label{eq:rate_calcs}
  \mft{r}_\mft{y} = \left[ \left( \frac{\mft{y}_2}{\mft{y}_1} \right) ^ \frac{\text{1}}{\mft{t}_2 - \mft{t}_1} - \text{1} \right] \times \text{100~\%/year} \; ,
\end{equation}
%
where
\mft{r} is the rate of change in \%/year;
\mft{y} is one of \ICOtwo{}, \mft{P}, \mft{A}, \REp{}, or \XCOtwo{}
for the prime example of energy and CO$_2$ emissions;
subscript ``2'' indicates a later year; and 
subscript ``1'' indicates an earlier year.

<<RatesOfChange>>=
rate_func <- function(df) {
  # Each df has structure
  # t1   y1
  # t2   y2
  yrs <- df[[2,1]] - df[[1,1]]
  # r = (y2/y1)^(1/t2-t1) - 1
  (df[[2,2]]/df[[1,2]])^(1/yrs) - 1
}

rate_to_string <- function(rate, include_units = TRUE) {
  if (include_units) {
    return(paste0(format(round(rate*100, 1), nsmall = 1), "\\%/yr"))
  }
  format(round(rate*100, 1), nsmall = 1)
}

